commit_message:
Adding new tables for future consumption

In ovsfw code, we've introduced new tables ACCEPTED_EGRESS_TRAFFIC_TABLE,
ACCEPTED_INGRESS_TRAFFIC_TABLE, DROPPED_TRAFFIC_TABLE for future
consumption like logging [1]. This patch adopts that to firewall driver
based OVS, then the issue related to security group logging which is specified
in release note of co-existence patch will be fixed.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/neutron/commit/65bde9f769e2ac18cb2684595000f92440f774d9

Co-Authored-By: Chandan Dutta Chowdhury <chandanc@juniper.net>

Change-Id: Ie673de416b67aceb2401d6fb8485dcb4f36a3d07

commit_message:
Apply default firewall group for new VM ports

The default fwg will be applied to all new VM ports within
a project if option auto_association_default_firewall_group
is enabled. This provides a way for a tenant network admin
to define a tenant wide firewall policy that applies to all
new VM ports.

Co-Authored-By: Nguyen Phuong An <AnNP@vn.fujitsu.com>

Partial-Implements: blueprint fwaas-api-2.0
Change-Id: I9e897444cd63e44c3274cdc9efedb35f8b325d1f

> Do we want to test these methods in backends since we're adding a couple schema tests or do we want to hold of on that until we do the manager?

Our tests are super confusing but the way it seems to be organized (well, half of it is organized this way and the other half someone probably meant to clean up like this) is there is a test_backends.py that tests all the manager functionality and then a backends/test_sql.py or a test_backend_sql.py that inherits from the manager tests, running all the core tests for a given driver. So the sql drivers themselves don't have a ton of tests. It threw me off but in a way it kind of makes sense because if the sql drivers had their own tests there would be a lot of duplicate tests testing the same thing. So the tests for this are in the following patch. If you have an idea of tests that should belong just to the sql driver feel free to propose it."}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2018-01-09 09:13:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 18: Patch Set 17 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2018-01-09 23:32:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 19.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2018-01-10 09:17:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 20: Patch Set 19 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 8482, 'date': '2018-01-10 13:09:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 21: Patch Set 20 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 5046, 'date': '2018-01-11 19:28:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

commit_message:
Update default value for derive params workflow inputs

This change is to update the default value for derive params
workflow inputs num_phy_cores_per_numa_node_for_pmd
and huge_page_allocation_percentage.
num_phy_cores_per_numa_node_for_pmd default value needs to be reduced
to 1 and cannot use more than 1 because of multi-queues.
huge_page_allocation_percentage default value needs to be reduced
from 90 because in some cases where we do not have enough memory
for some hosts

Change-Id: I8620f07f09337d0d63198c3168fec00f16262a63
Closes-Bug: #1736713

commit_message:
Expand note about rfc5988 link header

An alternate that is suggested for people who cannot add link sections
to the response body is the RFC 5988 Link header.

Move it to its own section for ease of linking, and change the text from
'can consider' to 'should'.

Also, add a note about API breakage and versioning related to adding
Link headers.

Change-Id: Ide4124513e3328084c53a2122384a4e25ea6c863

commit_message:
placement: _get_trees_matching_all_resources()

Adds a utility function in nova/objects/resource_provider.py that
returns the set of root_provider_id values representing provider trees
that can COLLECTIVELY satisfy a request for resources.

commit_message:

The development of craton has stopped around March 2017, we can retire
the repositories now.

This is the first step in retiring them.

See also

executables by calling the executable directly rather than

commit_message:
Add a guideline about use of the service catalog

The service catalog is an essential part of all API interactions,
but it's use is largely freeform (or cargo-culted based on what's in
devstack) Add specific guidlines for the catalogs of the future.

Split out the information from the discoverability document that was
talking about service catalog things and put it here.

Also, update a few examples in the code to be on endpoints that don't
have ports, so that we don't accidentally continue to recommend ports.

Change-Id: I60fe5e32ea895bbdf9508b23983b13b6619b1c4f

commit_message:
Fix starting hive failure in Ubuntu xenial

The mysql configuration file name and directory change in
Ubuntu 16.04. my.cnf becomes an entry for mysql configuration.
The new file locates here:
  "/etc/mysql/mysql.conf.d/mysqld.cnf"

Change-Id: I8f70589cfc904a7d30081172b313ad8e30914935
Closes-Bug: #1738124

subject: Don't make async_pendings during object expiration
messages:
[{'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-10 03:29:50.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-10 18:09:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-10 22:21:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

probe test doesn't work for me - we have an issue faking across layers

https://gist.github.com/clayg/b96c669e53b88ced82deca40a2d6d76f

^ should do it"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-11 00:25:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

You're completely right. I'd written that setdefault() call and it made my probetest pass, but I must have screwed up committing it.

I'll apply your patch and resubmit."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-11 00:26:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-11 20:32:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3: Patch Set 2 was rebased.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-11 20:49:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

(3 comments)

this change is just absolutely essential'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2018-01-12 18:36:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

(3 comments)

looks good in principle but I have not had time today to fully functionally test'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-12 23:49:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-12 23:49:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Fixed the commit message (thanks to Alistair for spotting the bug) and rebased. No other changes.'}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-01-13 01:27:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Happy to +2 once we tighten up the probe test a little.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2018-01-15 15:36:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I think there is a problem with this change. IF the expirer direct delete of the queue entry fails on its first attempt:

- expirer successfully delete expired object
- no async updates written
- expirer pop_queue fails (container servers down), entry remains in queue
- next cycle, expirer gets a 412 when attempting to delete the object
- also, it retries the DELETE by default 3 times!
- while expiry time > now - reclaim age, expirer does not attempt to pop_queue
- exception logged
- and so on until reclaim age passes

Previously the async update would have cleared the queue entry.

It's hard to write a probe test for this because it requires container servers to go down between the expirer reading the queue and trying to pop the queue, or for the container server connections to timeout for the pop queue direct deletes.

Perhaps the server could be smarter before raising a 412, and compare the req-if-delete-at with the tombstone time?? If the expirer attempts to delete an object a delete-at = t1 but the object has already been deleted at t1, that ought to be ok??"}, {'account_id': 15343, 'date': '2018-01-15 17:04:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

> next cycle, expirer gets a 412 when attempting to delete the object

Yeah, that's weird -- my gut says that should be a 404 (like what happens after the tombstone's been reclaimed), but sure enough, we'll totally 412 on a tombstone...

Though, of course, we'll still need to be able to handle 412s (since we may not have cleaned up the queue properly after setting a new x-delete-at, particularly following https://review.openstack.org/#/c/532342/).

> also, it retries the DELETE by default 3 times!

Depending on the nature of the failures, that's maybe not insane -- but retrying on 412 (and 404, and probably 4xx in general) is just wasteful. We *got* an authoritative answer, the retry will surely get the same response.

> while expiry time > now - reclaim age, expirer does not attempt to pop_queue

This seems particularly problematic -- it means expirers are perpetually running behind. *That* in turn makes the choice of X-Timestamp during the expirer's delete risky, because there's a risk that the tombstone would be immediately reclaimed! I remember some Rackers warning me about that back when I was reviewing https://review.openstack.org/#/c/283351/ but I couldn't come up with a better solution -- we'd either risk deleting data that shouldn't be deleted, or risk *not* deleting data that should've been deleted, and I feel like we oughta err on the side of not deleting enough data.

Is this just a consequence of us lumping 4xx in with "unexpected failures"? Or is there some other reason we might want this, like wanting to try *really really* hard to make sure that we didn't have all copies written to handoffs? If the former, then if/when we come up with good handling of totally-reasonable response codes, I think we can get away with leaving *this part* as-is.

Speaking of handling the totally-reasonable-and-not-at-all-unexpected, how about something like

- In the object-server, DELETE with X-If-Delete-At to a tombstone always 404s. There's no metadata to tell us whether X-Delete-At matches X-If-Delete-At or not; the thing's just gone.
- In the object-server, DELETE to an object with an *earlier* X-Delete-At 204s and we process the delete. The thing was supposed to be gone already, let's remove it. (Not actually sure this is a problem? Maybe unnecessary.)
- In the object-expirer, treat all of 204, 404, and 412 as success and pop the queue. 404 is successful on the grounds that we wanted it gone and it's gone; 412 is successful on the grounds that the current work item is resolved -- either the object is no longer scheduled to be deleted or there's some later work item already enqueued. In the eventually-consistent case of a .data that should get deleted but it doesn't have the .meta that would allow it, we assume that one of the other replicas *does* service the request, and that result will eventually get replicated out.

> exception logged

See https://review.openstack.org/#/c/496534/ -- I oughta rebase that. Oh, hey, and we've got https://bugs.launchpad.net/swift/+bug/1688558 and https://bugs.launchpad.net/swift/+bug/1455221 !'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-16 00:14:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(4 comments)

The expirer will continue to make progress even in the presence of bogus rows in its queue, i.e. ones where the row's timestamp does not match the object's X-Delete-At or ones where the object does not exist.

Really, "queue" is a misnomer. It's not a queue; you don't have to process the entries in order. It's a totally-ordered set of DB rows, and the expirer operates on the subset of rows meeting the criterion (row-delete-at <= now). Probably too late to fix the naming now, though. What I'm trying to say is that, even with all the log spew from 412s and 404s, the expirer will make progress. A 412 response won't stop it from processing the rest of the DB rows in the ready-to-expire subset.

Also, the expirer only leaves such rows in the DBs if the row timestamp is new enough. Once the row timestamp is less than (now - reclaim_age), it'll get thrown away.

Given that the above is true and I haven't misunderstood things, the expirer will still make progress even with the bogus rows in its DBs, so the occasional absence of async_pendings from this patch will not break things. In some cases, it'll make more work for the expirer's container DBs, and in some cases, it'll make less work. I think it'll average out to less.

That said, the expirer's logging and queue-management logic certainly needs improvement. I believe that can be done in parallel with this change without any coordination.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-16 00:14:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2018-01-16 09:43:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

I think I'd be happy to take this if we land all three -- but if we're doing it piecemeal... I need to think a little more about it, and how much explaining we'll have to do about all the tracebacks.

And on my thoughts about changes to the object-server, looks like keeping the work job around on 404/412 was a conscious decision (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/326903/) that has been reaffirmed previously (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/486599/)... Maybe there's some special case that could be carved out when x-if-delete-at == on-disk ts timestamp? And we should really consider a 409 successful..."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-16 19:57:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

I think i hear where acoles is coming from - but AFAIK we're talking about inefficiencies not correctness.  Either solution is correct, one optimizes for the happy path one optimizes for the failure condition.  I'd rather have a failed pop_queue request result in a row hanging around for a reclaim than every expirier delete result in async pendings and all those useless container updates that go along with it.

[{'created': '2018-01-10 03:29:50.000000000', 'message': "Don't make async_pendings during object expiration

After deleting an object, the object expirer deletes the corresponding

container server requests to Rc (typically 3), all issued directly
from the object expirer.

commit_message:
Don't make async_pendings during object expiration

After deleting an object, the object expirer deletes the corresponding
row from the expirer queue by making DELETE requests directly to the
container servers. The same thing happens after attempting to delete
an object, but failing because the object has already been deleted. If
the DELETE requests fail, then the expirer will encounter that row
again on its next pass and retry the DELETE at that time. Therefore,
it is not necessary for the object server to write an async_pending
for that queue row's deletion.

Currently, however, two of the object servers do write such
async_pendings. Given Rc container replicas, that's 2 * Rc updates
from async_pendings and another Rc from the object expirer
directly. Given a typical Rc of 3, that's 9 container updates per
expiring object.

This commit makes the object server write no async_pendings for DELETE
requests coming from the object expirer. This reduces the number of
container server requests to Rc (typically 3), all issued directly
from the object expirer.

Closes-Bug: 1076202
Change-Id: Icd63c80c73f864d2561e745c3154fbfda02bd0cc

[{'created': '2018-01-03 16:56:20.000000000', 'message': "Avoid loading nested stack in some grouputils functions

We want to avoid loading a nested stack in memory wherever possible, since
that is known to cause memory high-water-mark issues. The grouputils
functions are among the worst offenders at doing this. Some of the data
that they return is easily obtained from an RPC call to
list_stack_resources, so swap out the implementations using nested().

Rather than simply add more utility functions, a GroupInspector class is
created that can cache the data returned. In future this will allow groups
that need to access multiple functions from the grouputils to do so without
making multiple RPC calls. (Previously, the data was cached in the group's
nested Stack.)

Change-Id: Icd35d91bce30ee36d9592b0516767ef273a9f34d
Partial-Bug: #1731349

commit_message:
Avoid loading nested stack in some grouputils functions

We want to avoid loading a nested stack in memory wherever possible, since
that is known to cause memory high-water-mark issues. The grouputils
functions are among the worst offenders at doing this. Some of the data
that they return is easily obtained from an RPC call to
list_stack_resources, so swap out the implementations using nested().

Rather than simply add more utility functions, a GroupInspector class is
created that can cache the data returned. In future this will allow groups
that need to access multiple functions from the grouputils to do so without
making multiple RPC calls. (Previously, the data was cached in the group's
nested Stack.)

Change-Id: Icd35d91bce30ee36d9592b0516767ef273a9f34d
Partial-Bug: #1731349

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-17 15:57:53.000000000', 'message': 'Partially Revert "Update new documentation PTI jobs"

The zuul job figures out whether to run "setup.py build_sphinx" or
"build-sphinx" based on whether the project is relying on pbr's
ability to auto-generate API reference docs. Because we are relying on
that, we want local builds to use "setup.py build_sphinx".

This reverts commit 42e0037cd055d81d9452f046c347f8e469d27350.

Change-Id: Ia01188110fa9c3ccaf3d794fa3a511a6780e683e
'}]
commit_message:
Partially Revert "Update new documentation PTI jobs"

The zuul job figures out whether to run "setup.py build_sphinx" or
"build-sphinx" based on whether the project is relying on pbr's
ability to auto-generate API reference docs. Because we are relying on
that, we want local builds to use "setup.py build_sphinx".

This reverts commit 42e0037cd055d81d9452f046c347f8e469d27350.

Change-Id: Ia01188110fa9c3ccaf3d794fa3a511a6780e683e

nova-manage map_instances maps all instances into a cell in batches
of 50 if max-count is not set. Setting max-count causes the script
to run a single batch of size max-count. The return code of the
script shows if there are still more to do. This change runs
map_instances repeatedly with a batch size of 50000 while rc is 1
and then exists cleanly when a rc 0 is recieved.

commit_message:
Batch up map_instances call

nova-manage map_instances maps all instances into a cell in batches
of 50 if max-count is not set. Setting max-count causes the script
to run a single batch of size max-count. The return code of the
script shows if there are still more to do. This change runs
map_instances repeatedly with a batch size of 50000 while rc is 1
and then exists cleanly when a rc 0 is recieved.

Change-Id: Id1184778a5ae94bb3b57348b10d12077b093d6dd
Partial-Bug: #1742115

[{'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-09-29 10:50:10.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-29 11:15:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/07/124707/1/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/3e62968/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 2m 47s'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-09-29 16:27:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

While possibly convenient, this seems to be able to be accomplished today with a stack-update setting the deletion policy to retain for the resource to "abandon". Then simply issue a stack-update excluding the abandoned resources. Adopting a single resource for an existing stack could be accomplished by abandoning the stack and altering the adopt data to include both the desired template changes as well as any additional resource data.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-09-30 05:00:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Hi Randall Burt,
In the existing approach, the complete stack needs to be abandoned before updating(#1) or adopting(#2), while user wanted to adopt even a single resource. To avoid that, this bule-print has been proposed with following advantages: 
1. user experience: user can directly adopt/abandon a resource easily in a give stack.
2. Turn-around time: It reduces the complete turn-around time of a adoption/abandon a resource as it avoids the complete stack abandon and re-creation.

In addition, as part of the stack-update, 'adopt_stack_data' also could be enabled as part of this blue-print."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-09-30 16:37:25.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

While I agree that it might be more convenient from a UX perspective, it still boils down to the same operations (update delete policy, update stack, etc) and doesn't necessarily save much in the way of operational overhead."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-10-01 05:30:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-01 05:33:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Build failed.  For information on how to proceed, see https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GerritJenkinsGit#Test_Failures

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/07/124707/2/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/18faf12 : FAILURE in 1m 44s'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-10-01 05:46:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I am a bit concerned that we are proposing extensions to a feature that is working poorly/not well maintained.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-10-01 06:23:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-10-01 06:24:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/07/124707/3/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/51c5d54/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 46s'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-06 17:43:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> I am a bit concerned that we are proposing extensions to a feature that is working poorly/not well maintained.

+1 I'm also not keen on adding anything else related to abandon/adopt until we resolve all the issues with the existing functionality."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-10-06 18:31:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

While I understand those concerns, should we assess this proposal on its merrits? I get that there are issues with abandon/adopt and those should absolutely get addressed before more features are added, but that shouldn't hold up this proposal, should it?"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-06 19:34:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

> While I understand those concerns, should we assess this proposal on its merrits? ... but that shouldn't hold up this proposal, should it?

It shouldn't hold up discussion of this idea, but IMO it should postpone approval of this BP, maybe this should be marked WIP until we make some progress on solving the abandon/adopt bugs?

I guess the issue is, approving a spec sends the message that we'll merge the code if it shows up and is correctly implemented, only in this case we probably won't, because the whole feature is so broken we're talking about disabling it by default, and has been for an entire cycle with very slow progress on resolving the issues identified."}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-10-06 19:44:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Agreed then. I would support marking this as WiP and holding off on approval until the other issues are sorted.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-10-06 20:08:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(10 comments)'}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-10-13 02:28:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

As an alternative (that i think solve quite a few user related questions i have heard of) would be to have a way to do this within the template instead of at the api layer. So many people have network discovery and user discovery code so they can passin the the right thing. ATM we are not very declarative, using the below we could create-if-needed.

  my_net:
    type: OS::Neutron::Network
    adopt_data: {OS::Neurton::find_net: [args]}
    parameters:
      bla (used if can't be adopted)"}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-10-13 07:30:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hi Angus,

your proposal helps to incorporate the changes at the heat-api layer. I will update the blueprint with this mentioning in place, in addition to Steven hardy's comments appropriately.

Thanks."}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-10-14 11:02:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2014-10-14 11:03:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
heat resource abandon and adopt

For the existing resource, user may wants to abandon a given
resource in a stack or adopt a new resource into a stack as
the child of one of the existing resource or stack itself.
This can be useful to bring a resource under control of
the stack, or remove it from the stack non-destructively.

Co-Authored-By: Johnson koil raj <johnson.raj@hp.com>
Change-Id: I7ba0172254b8ddb229d6bba70675bc2314257493

commit_message:
Run overcloud-upgrade role only in upgrades jobs.

Defined tags are the same for all multinode
jobs, independently on if they perform an
upgrade or not. Each featureset env file then
defines if an upgrade is to be performed or not,
being skipped all the tasks of the overcloud-upgrade
role if it's not an upgrades job.

This task skipping takes around 3 seconds,
what's not a big deal, but it makes the logs
more difficult to read and understand.

This patch appends the overcloud-upgrade role
into the tags only if the job to be run performs
an upgrade.

Change-Id: Ia037dd74470499d302cb098136fbe71608b7824a

This reverts commit 5eba5cf39238b7f4410c66c0b61262ce12c87890
and thus restores the original "Add support for monasca-ui
metrics API proxy" patch
(bb5178406c03d37a957b64ef59c61ecdec504fc3). It is best to fix
this problem in Keystone patched Grafana:

https://github.com/monasca/grafana/pull/1

Hmm, turns out this shows a difference in behaviour between the enforcement of self-referential foreign key constraints in MySQL and SQLite. There are existing functional tests in nova/tests/functional/db/test_resource_provider.py that delete providers -- even ones that have root_provider_id == id -- and don't trigger this bug. So, it must be a MySQL-ism (maybe PostgreSQL-ism as well).

I'd much prefer to see a functional test of this, but our functional testing suite is primarily designed for SQLite and it would be problematic to try and add a test to nova/tests/functional/db/test_resource_provider.py that only ran on MySQL...

So, I suppose I am OK with this fix and unit test as it is.

Thanks, Andrey and Kero!

-jay"}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2018-01-11 01:15:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

[{'created': '2017-12-21 09:15:00.000000000', 'message': 'Clean up foreign key before root resource provider deleting

Current, we can't delete the root resource provider record
because it has a foreign key reference it id on itself, we will
get back DBReferenceError, the reason is "Cannot delete or
update a parent row: a foreign key constraint fails".

This patch fix this bug, if we find the record is the root
resource provider(id == root_provider_id), we clean up this
foreign key first, and then delete it.

Closes-Bug:#1739571
Change-Id: I256c901fdc02b1f764ea9f8d1a1a708e82cc369a

commit_message:
[placement] Fix resource provider delete

Due to foreign key constraints for the
resource_provider.root_provider_id in mysql and the way of column
filling it is impossible to delete newly created RP now.

Patch sets root_provider_id to NULL before deletion
if root_provider_id == id.

Closes-Bug: #1739571
Co-Authored-by: Andrey Volkov <avolkov@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I256c901fdc02b1f764ea9f8d1a1a708e82cc369a

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Implement IPv6 support for Dell EMC VNX driver

Major changes:
  * Support to create/delete/extend/access NFS and CIFS share/snapshot
    in the IPv6 network which created by Neutron
  * Support to connect VNX management interface using IPv6 address

Change-Id: Ibe7620f9548d5f57780e49c08214dc627b91a945
Implements: blueprint vnx-manila-ipv6-support

commit_message:
Fix wrong error message for secgroup_rule method

In method `create_sec_group_rule`, when add_rule raise error.
The error message would confuse the user, it failed to create
secgroup_rule, not secgroup. In method `delete` of class
`SecurityGroupRule` is the same problem, fail delete a secgroup rule,
not a secgroup.

Change-Id: Id5ad4a7b8a4d292ba0a0bef5231db8d6af8eb29a

commit_message:
Allow overriding app cred restrictions

If a user creates an application credential with flag
`allow_application_credential_creation` then that application should be
allowed to be used for creating and deleting other application
credentials and trusts. Ensure a flag is set in the token if this
property is set to allow this behavior.

Change-Id: Ibb62d10aafa84b38c797b795c798df43dea66a2a

commit_message:
Set shard range state during sharding

Use shard range state to differentiate between shards that have been
found and had their container CREATED, and those that have also been
cleaved and are ACTIVE. This allows the root container to only
consider ACTIVE shard ranges when serving GET and HEAD requests.

Shard ranges cease to be ACTIVE when for example they are SHRUNK.

Listing a container while it is partially sharding now requires
the final part of the listing to be supplied by the sharding
container. This was apparently broken because that final
partial listing request sent '&end_marker=None' (yes, the
string None).

Change-Id: I436ce26742894b3e85560d4c007d386da55cdf29

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-05 19:52:07.000000000', 'message': 'Add state and state_timestamp to ShardRange

Add a state attribute to ShardRange and a state_timestamp so that
updates to the state can be tracked independently of updates to the
shard namespace and shard metadata.

When a shard is sharded, new shard containers are created that will
update the root shard range table with their metadata (object count
etc). But until *all* the new shard containers have been created and
cleaved we need the root to exclude these shard ranges when compiling
container stats, since they overlap with the still existent original
shard. Once all new shards have been created and cleaved, the sharding
shard should inform the root to henceforth exclude itself and include
the new shard range stats.

This is achieved by adding a state attribute to ShardRange. The root
container will exclude shard ranges in CREATED state, but include
shard ranges in the ACTIVE state. The sharding shard updates the state
of all the new shard ranges that it has cleaved to ACTIVE while
simultaneously updating its own state to RETIRED. It must do this
without modifying the created or meta timestamps of the shard ranges:
increasing the created timestamp would cause updates from the new
shard containers to be ignored as obsolete; increasing the meta
timestamp would potentially write stale object stats to the root shard
range table.

For example, initially the root shard range table includes a shard
that is ready to be sharded:

sr_lower_upper : <lower-upper @ t0, meta @ t0, state=ACTIVE  @ t0>

Shard sr_lower_upper shards into sr_lower_mid and sr_mid_upper:
initially the new shard ranges are put to the root with timestamp t2
and the shard containers are created with timestamp t1; updates from
the new containers to the root are ignored since t1 < t2, which is
desirable because the new containers have not yet had objects cleaved
to them. The root shard table now includes:

sr_lower_upper : <lower-upper @ t0, meta @ t0, state=ACTIVE  @ t0>
sr_lower_mid   : <lower-mid   @ t2, meta @ t2, state=CREATED @ t2>
sr_mid_upper   : <mid-upper   @ t2, meta @ t2, state=CREATED @ t2>

Only sr_lower_upper is included when calculating root container stats.

Now, one of the new shard ranges is cleaved, sr_lower_mid, which
causes its containers shard created timestamp to move to t2 via
replication. Metadata updates at t3 from that container to the root
now succeed, which is desirable because the shard may be receiving new
object updates, and eventually we want the root to have the up to date
stats. However, the shard range must still be excluded from the root
stats because it overlaps with the historic sr_lower_upper.

sr_lower_upper : <lower-upper @ t0, meta @ t0, state=ACTIVE  @ t0>
sr_lower_mid   : <lower-mid   @ t2, meta @ t3, state=CREATED @ t2>
sr_mid_upper   : <mid-upper   @ t2, meta @ t2, state=CREATED @ t2>

The second shard range is cleaved, its shard containers get shard
created timestamp t2 via replication, and metadata updates at t4 now
succeed at the root:

sr_lower_upper : <lower-upper @ t0, meta @ t0, state=ACTIVE  @ t0>
sr_lower_mid   : <lower-mid   @ t2, meta @ t3, state=CREATED @ t2>
sr_mid_upper   : <mid-upper   @ t2, meta @ t4, state=CREATED @ t2>

Still only sr_lower_upper is included when calculating root container stats.

The original shard is now fully sharded and updates the root shard
ranges:

sr_lower_upper : <lower-upper @ t0, meta @ t0, state=RETIRED @ t5>
sr_lower_mid   : <lower-mid   @ t2, meta @ t3, state=ACTIVE @ t5>
sr_mid_upper   : <mid-upper   @ t2, meta @ t4, state=ACTIVE @ t5>

Change-Id: I1aa9ef01508a65949615a24aaef472820d6f30c8

commit_message:
Add state and state_timestamp to ShardRange

Add a state attribute to ShardRange and a state_timestamp so that
updates to the state can be tracked independently of updates to the
shard namespace and shard metadata.

Change-Id: I1aa9ef01508a65949615a24aaef472820d6f30c8

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-12-14 23:21:33.000000000', 'message': 'Parameterize ceph-ansible forks in Tripleo Heat templates

The number of ansible forks is set to the number of unique hosts
or CephAnsibleForksMax, whichever is smaller. CephAnsibleForksMax
used to be hard set to 100. This change keeps that default but
allows the user to override the CephAnsibleForksMax. Also, allow
user to override this logic and set the CephAnsibleForks directly.
Also allows user to pass ssh_retries.

Depends-On: I5d69af146ca6ca8b3d5f78445cd1b47828daa955
Change-Id: Ic731c8f0c988c485c5b3448182a568b8514cab0a

commit_message:
Parameterize ceph-ansible environment variables

Add CephAnsibleEnvironmentVariables which allows a user to
override any Ansible environment variable.

Depends-On: I5d69af146ca6ca8b3d5f78445cd1b47828daa955

Closes-Bug: 1738276

commit_message:
Add support to accept custom connector object

There are libraries which use Sushy to connect to Redfish based
systems. At times there arises some need for those extension
libraries to pass on their custom made Connector objects which
can extend the functionality of Sushy connector. For instance,
refer [0]. Hence, adding the support to accept custom connector
object in Sushy's constructor.

[0] https://github.com/openstack/proliantutils/blob/master/proliantutils/redfish/connector.py

Change-Id: I220b44b2c5a65b0ee410097594a5a87dd87e4753

commit_message:
Fix address format used in find_best_address()

The current implementation only works for IPv6 addresses, for IPv4
addresses the connect() call always produces an exception because the
address format is wrong. We need to use the format matching the address
family that is being used.

Change-Id: Ida5099278363dc4a527bb488c83883a1d2377f6b
Story: 2001475
Task: 6195

commit_message:
Setting streaming options as not required

streaming_mapper and steraming_reducer as not marked as not required,
this causes UI to crash when trying to launch job that are not Streaming
MapReduce jobs.

commit_message:
Simplify logic in wait_for_disk_to_become_available

 * Simplify the logic in utils.py/wait_for_disk_to_become_available
 * Correct unit tests to not use None as a return value for calls to
   utils.execute() that return no output. In reality utils.execute()
   will return empty strings for example: ('', '')
 * Add unit tests to test 'psmisc' and 'busybox' versions of output
   data from 'fuser'
 * Add a shorter check device interval as test was taking over 2
   seconds and showing up in longest test run time list.

Change-Id: Ibc481e4a76c63612e1774b5c7a8144ee934eb2f5

commit_message:
Fix up to work with 0.6.0 of charms.reactive

charms.reactive deprecates the RelationBase.from_state() class
method.  This is an internal method in charms.reactive and shouldn't
have been used.

This patch changes charms.openstack to use
charms.relations.endpoint_from_flag(...) which essentially does the
same thing and will be a more stable API moving forwards.

Note that from this point on, the library will ONLY work with
charms.reactive 0.6.0 onwards.

Change-Id: I20b8a6978b83d9ec075817e929fa86d3a3ae828a

commit_message:
Add openstack_ca_file configuration option

In the drivers section of magnum.conf add openstack_ca_file.
This file is expected to be a CA Certificate OR CA bundle
which will be passed on every node and it will be installed
on the host's CA bundle.

Update devstack plugin to use the ssl bundle if tls-proxy is
enabled.

Install the CA for drivers:
k8s_coreos_v1
k8s_fedora_atomic_v1
k8s_fedora_ironic_v1
mesos_ubuntu_v1
swarm_fedora_atomic_v1
swarm_fedora_atomic_v2

Add doc in troubleshooting-guide.

Add release notes.

Closes-Bug: #1580704
Partially-Implements: blueprint heat-agent
Change-Id: Id48fbea187da667a5e7334694c3ec17c8e2504db

commit_message:
Import user and admin guide from horizon

User and admin guide was moved accidentally from openstack-manuals
to horizon during the doc-migration in Pike. This commit moves them
from horizon to manila-ui repository for better future maintenance.

commit_message:
Reorganize manila-ui documentation

This commit reorganizes the doc structure in the way
suggested by doc-migration spec.

Note that user/ is not touched by this commit
as I plan to update it in a subsequent patch
which moves manila-ui user/admin guide from horizon.

Change-Id: I3c644c33cb912397bd1d5ee890f4991ac3e26501

commit_message:
Resolve redefinition issue for ganesha VIP

After a recent change[1] to configure VIPs for isolated
networks via a hiera parameter containing the networks
rather than using hard-coded networks the (optional)
ganesha VIP used by the ceph nfs manila back end still
defined the VIP separately, resulting in overcloud deploy
failure due to attempted redefinition of the same VIP.

Remove the hard-coded definition of ganesha VIP in favor
of the new VIP definition mode.

Closes-Bug: #1743863

[1] I117454afe750451ad1f2633fa0f196bb71740b8d

Change-Id: I0e204b44c24e504ef00537ebd4ecea21ca6a63ec

commit_message:
Workflow execution blacklist support

Workflows triggered from deploy-steps.j2 were not honoring the
blacklist, particularly ceph-ansible. This patch starts to address that
issue by passing in a list of blacklisted ip addresses to the workflow
execution environment that the workflow can make use of to filter
against ctlplane_service_ips.

Change-Id: Ic158171c629e82892e480f1e6903a67457f86064
Partial-Bug: #1743046

We were excluding 'INSTANCE_6'from scope, which belongs to 'NODE_3'
in scenerio_1.xml [1]. But NODE_3 is removed from model before only

So, This Patch adds 'AZ3' in fake_scope.

commit_message:
Fix compute scope test bug

We were excluding 'INSTANCE_6'from scope, which belongs to 'NODE_3'
in scenerio_1.xml [1]. But NODE_3 is removed from model before only
as it is not in scope.

So, This Patch adds 'AZ3' in fake_scope.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/watcher/blob/master/watcher/tests/decision_engine/model/data/scenario_1.xml
Closes-Bug: #1737901

Change-Id: Ib1aaca7045908418ad0c23b718887cd89db98a83

commit_message:
Allow ssh utils to use an absolute path

Currently, the ssh utils only accept a filename, and defaults to the
user's home directory + '.ssh'. The user should be allowed to put
the ssh key in whatever directory they choose.

Change-Id: I4a3068cbe765a16f6ba4b0c3e38410929ca3a14c
Needed-By: I7eaff91b3bc3b94ca97ffc7a1ace74c86117bd07

commit_message:
Make Horizon parameters: vhost_extra_params and customization_module configurable

Horizon parameters - horizon::vhost_extra_params and horizon::customization_module
are available but not configurable using horizon. This change exposes these parameters
and makes them configurable.

Depends-On: Id204b60b2676f49713fb6ce7eede6200221f7163
Change-Id: I4875585530c6d1d3b1134577ef2e097216c6c348
(cherry picked from commit b27cc34d8b8787b30e856b427fd03ca462661ac8)

commit_message:
Relocate branch conditional for tempest-full job

This condition was added to openstack-zuul-jobs in [1], but it created
bug #1739829 as a side effect. While addressing the issue [2] it was
noticed  that conditional could be located in the tempest repo itself,
so this patch aims at cleaning things up a bit and reduce the moving
parts.

[1] I799ea86f3c445bb067950a8cbc237999d621e3a9
[2] I5d34e5b983b720dc1913d00ccc1a16d81a040d49
Needed-by: Ibfbc925af6eb274ced53312301b1733136ba4455
Partial-bug: #1739829

Change-Id: I8e0aa11cd2d92d5d6f5e9147a407374948920e7f

commit_message:
Avoid global LOGGER instance

We should not use global variable as possible. This patch removes
the LOGGER global variable. And then, add get_logger to some places
that need to log.

Change-Id: I6041cfa10a2e2461b87d3fae9bc453858f03ace2

messages:
[{'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-11 21:37:05.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-11 22:05:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

it'd fix the specific gate failure in http://logs.openstack.org/74/532174/1/gate/cross-swift-py27/cc370d3/job-output.txt.gz#_2018-01-11_20_07_17_851149, so it's at least no worse than before."}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2018-01-12 01:36:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Still fails fairly regularly to me.. sure a little less often. So based on that, it's better then we have so maybe I should +2/+A.

However, inline I mention another approach changing the delta a little. So will -1. But if my maths is wrong, or there is a reason for the delta of 5, I'm happy to be veto'ed in which case can change my vote :)"}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2018-01-12 05:12:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

garr, after approx 1000 runs of the test I got a difference of 10:

  In [1]: _partition_counts(rb, 'ip')
  Out[1]: 
  Counter({'127.0.0.3': 410,
           '127.0.0.4': 410,
           '127.1.1.5': 392,
           '127.1.2.1': 418,
           '127.1.2.2': 418})

  In [2]: expected
  Out[2]: 
  {'127.0.0.3': 410,
   '127.0.0.4': 410,
   '127.1.1.5': 402,
   '127.1.2.1': 413,
   '127.1.2.2': 412}

Note the r1 z1 host:

  '127.1.1.5': 392 (actual) and 402 (expected).

Maybe 1 in 1000 isn't so bad. I'll leave the debug session up incase I want to poke closer to see exactly what happened later.. but can't now as I need to go do some non Swift stuff they're paying me to do :("}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 01:19:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I wonder why there is so much variance in this particular rebalance... 

I'm mostly find with pushing Delta up as high as needed - I wish we had a better way to see the center..."}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2018-01-17 20:03:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm fine with cranking the delta up as well."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 21:36:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

this is biting us quite often:

2018-01-17 18:49:19.730266 | ubuntu-xenial | >>  raise self.failureException('part counts not close enough to expected:\nparts in 127.1.1.5 was 395 expected 401')

http://logs.openstack.org/83/532383/8/check/swift-tox-py27/9e0687d/job-output.txt.gz

I had also considered if we increase the part power of the test ring it might naturally smooth out a bit more..."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 23:19:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 23:21:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

so i doubled the parts twice, and only had to double the delta once to get it through a 100x w/o failure

I also updated the failure assertion message so it was easier to see how parts were sliding around - it's a little frustrating that it's so non-deterministic - there's a pretty big difference in balance between the far ends...

it's possible doing successive rebalances would close the delta even further..."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 23:21:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

torolololo

    AssertionError: some part counts not close enough to expected:
    parts in 127.0.0.1 was 1639 expected 1638 (ok)
    parts in 127.0.0.2 was 1638 expected 1638 (ok)
    parts in 127.1.1.3 was 1598 expected 1610 (!=)
    parts in 127.1.2.4 was 1659 expected 1653 (ok)
    parts in 127.1.2.5 was 1658 expected 1653 (ok)'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 23:29:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2018-01-17 23:31:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2

ok, *now* were getting somewhere.  dispersion is garbage.  But the randomly being more or less balances makes sense to me.  We can make it more deterministic by letting it settle down before we put assertions on it.  The test still demonstrates that we're calculating dispersion "correctly" for a mixed topology.'}, {'account_id': 7233, 'date': '2018-01-18 06:15:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Workflow+1 Code-Review+2

Ran the test 4500 times and always passes. Nice. So upping the part_power smoothed it out it seems, and the letting settle.
Tho requiring multiple rebalances is a little annoying for someone creating a ring, they may assume it's new ring so surly it picked the best on initial rebalance and have never been told to run a rebalance more then once to settle and shake out a bit... well I know I don't on test clusters, but that's probably just my lack of OP experience showing.

However, knowing this now, I assume tools building _new_ rings for clusters should run rebalance until the balance is right.. and maybe I should go and add that ability to the Suse and OpenStack ansible swift playbooks :)

Or maybe when the ringbuilder rebalances for the first time, ie needs to go create a non existent brand new _replica2parts2dev it should rebalance until things stop moving... assuming there is no edge case where things will always move :P

Anyway, I've rambled enough. Definitely fixes the intermittent problem. Nice one Clay."}, {'account_id': 25747, 'date': '2018-01-18 06:19:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}]

commit_message:
Fix InternalClient to drain response body if the request fails

If we don't drain the body, the proxy logging in the internal client
pipeline will log 499 client disconnect instead of actual error response
code.

For error responses, we try to do the most helpful thing using swob's
closing and caching response body attribute.  For non-error responses
which are returned to the client, we endeavour to keep the app_iter
intact and unconsumed, trusting expecting the caller to do the right
thing is the only reasonable interface.  We must cleanly close any WSGI
app_iter which we do not return to the client regardless of status code
and allow the logging of the 499 if needed.

Closes-Bug: #1675650
Change-Id: I455b5c38074ad0e72aa5e0b05771e193208905eb

commit_message:
add _has_provider_trees() utility function

Adds a simple _has_provider_trees() function to
nova/objects/resource_provider.py that returns True if any provider has
a non-NULL parent_provider_id. This will allow future code to take
simpler, optimized code paths when retrieving allocation candidates and
the deployment is not using nested resource providers.

Change-Id: I7305c8c00dd5595dcbfc9ea551da33677dbf38dd
blueprint: nested-resource-providers

[{'created': '2018-01-03 02:55:19.000000000', 'message': 'Skip testcases when shared nets are found in AutoAllocateNetworkTest

Shared nets is common configuration for the system, e.g., if we set
create_isolated_networks = False, we will create a shared net for
all testcases/tenants to use, which is specified by fixed_network_name,
 cfg.StrOpt('fixed_network_name',
            help="Name of the fixed network that is visible to all test "
                 "projects. If multiple networks are available for a "
                 "project, this is the network which will be used for "
                 "creating servers if tempest does not create a network or "
                 "a network is not specified elsewhere. It may be used for "
                 "ssh validation only if floating IPs are disabled."),

So, when shared nets are found, we should skip the testcase instead of
raising an exception.

Change-Id: I44aa06c1e0b5fb1d58707605ca084b272223aaf7
'}]
commit_message:
Skip testcases when shared nets are found in AutoAllocateNetworkTest

Shared nets is common configuration for the system, e.g., if we set
create_isolated_networks = False, we will create a shared net for
all testcases/tenants to use, which is specified by fixed_network_name,
 cfg.StrOpt('fixed_network_name',
            help="Name of the fixed network that is visible to all test "
                 "projects. If multiple networks are available for a "
                 "project, this is the network which will be used for "
                 "creating servers if tempest does not create a network or "
                 "a network is not specified elsewhere. It may be used for "
                 "ssh validation only if floating IPs are disabled."),

So, when shared nets are found, we should skip the testcase instead of
raising an exception.

Change-Id: I44aa06c1e0b5fb1d58707605ca084b272223aaf7

commit_message:
Change Senlin Install documents

Separated devstack and manual installation.
Senlin in pike version support rdo install.
Add a new install way, use rdo install.

This url record senlin pike rpm address:
http://mirror.centos.org/centos/7/cloud/x86_64/openstack-pike/

This url record senlin rdo service address:
https://github.com/rdo-packages/senlin-distgit

Change-Id: I689862a0bc1b38d3e5f76f4eb237596bbf75f81d
Signed-off-by: Yuanbin.Chen <cybing4@gmail.com>

'}, {'created': '2018-01-15 17:44:39.000000000', 'message': 'Replace DeploymentEngine with EnvManager

It is impossible to replace the whole deployment component at once. At
least because we need to make it backward compatible.
This patch starts this effort.

What is done:
- the database layer is cleaned from deployments and resources tables.
  the api of database layer is also cleaned from deployment related
  things
  PS: all the current deploment records move to the env and platforms
      tables
- rally.common.objects.Deployment became a proxy layer between old world
  and new one (Environment component). It provides the full
  compatibility in terms of data and interfaces
- rally.api.API.deployment starts using some new interfaces of
  EnvManager directly, where it is possible

commit_message:
Replace DeploymentEngine with EnvManager

It is impossible to replace the whole deployment component at once. At
least because we need to make it backward compatible.
This patch starts this effort.

What is done:
- the database layer is cleaned from deployments and resources tables.
  the api of database layer is also cleaned from deployment related
  things
  PS: all the current deploment records move to the env and platforms
      tables
- rally.common.objects.Deployment became a proxy layer between old world
  and new one (Environment component). It provides the full
  compatibility in terms of data and interfaces
- rally.api.API.deployment starts using some new interfaces of
  EnvManager directly, where it is possible
- DeploymentEngine (with "ExistingCloud" plugin), CredentialsBuilder
  (with "openstack" plugin) are deleted.
  It should be noted in release notes...
- EnvManager starts cleaning verifier specific data as well..

Change-Id: If7bde619f7c2e99248a071ff18b8084553e1bec0

commit_message:
Add same extra specs as self.flavor_ref for created new flavor

In some environments, some extra specs must be set for the flavors
that will be used to create server, e.g., flavor extra specs
{"hw:mem_page_size": "large"} needs to be set if all compute nodes use
huge page and the system demmands explicit huge page filtering, in
this case if no {"hw:mem_page_size": "large"} extra specs is set for
the flavor, when creating server we will get
"BuildErrorException: Server 921aa25c-d182-4b53-88d1-90e003b17212 failed
                     to build and is in ERROR status
 Details: {'message': 'No valid host was found. There are not enough hosts
          available.', 'code': 500, 'created': '2017-12-14T05:33:52Z'}"

Another usecase is if there are many compute nodes, e.g., more than 20
compute nodes, we may want to limit the tempest execution on part of them
(maybe not all nodes are suitable for the test), so we can add
{"aggregate_instance_extra_specs:availability_zone": "tempest-zone"}
for the predefined flavor for it to choose only specified compute nodes.

Usually we will set the correct extra specs for the flavors that will
be filled as CONF.compute.flavor_ref and CONF.compute.flavor_ref_alt,
so it's ok to use these flavors to create servers, but if we need to
create a new flavor in testcases to create server, and if no extra specs
is set for it, creating server may fail.

So this is to add same extra specs as self.flavor_ref for the created
flavor that will be used to create server, and we don't need to do this
for those created flavors that won't be used to create servers.

Change-Id: I7dea2ef41bd686b544ead7f1ba0587720c3a3c44
Closes-bug: #1742132

commit_message:
Preserve expiring object behaviour with old proxy-server

The related change [1] causes expiring object records to no longer be
created if the X-Delete-At-Container header is not sent to the object
server, but old proxies prior to [2] (i.e. releases prior to 1.9.0)
did not send this header.

The goal of [1] can be alternatively achieved by making expiring
object record creation be conditional on the X-Delete-At-Host header.

[1] Related-Change: I20fc2f42f590fda995814a2fa7ba86019f9fddc1
[2] Related-Change: Id0873a3f2198ce285fe0b0c777738eff38bc2438

Change-Id: Ia0081693f01631d3f2a59612308683e939ced76a

The existing merge code was insufficient for merging records of the
same object that might have differing relative meta and content-type
timestamps.

had not yet been cleaved but might have recent objects updates that
are not in the root. The proxy no longer gets those shard ranges from

commit_message:
Don't attempt to merge root and shard listings in proxy

See https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/deep-container-listing

The existing merge code was insufficient for merging records of the
same object that might have differing relative meta and content-type
timestamps.

The merging was only necessary for shard ranges in CREATED state that
had not yet been cleaved but might have recent objects updates that
are not in the root. The proxy no longer gets those shard ranges from
the container serve so merging is not required.

Change-Id: Ied70aea3d0b077af484d7e1bb95d929a7fa927b0

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-09 10:48:34.000000000', 'message': 'VMAX driver - Multiple storage group creation attempts

When creating volumes concurrently on a clean system, we can see a
situation where multiple processes try and create the default storage
group simultaneously. This can lead to failures as attempts are made to
create the default storage group after another process has already
created the resource. This patch rectifies the issue by checking if the
storage group has been created by another process while we were waiting
for the lock.

Change-Id: Icb16b1be23a5dcce7303d7d132db5fd31b3e41f2
Closes-bug: 1742100
'}]
commit_message:
VMAX driver - Multiple storage group creation attempts

When creating volumes concurrently on a clean system, we can see a
situation where multiple processes try and create the default storage
group simultaneously. This can lead to failures as attempts are made to
create the default storage group after another process has already
created the resource. This patch rectifies the issue by checking if the
storage group has been created by another process while we were waiting
for the lock.

Change-Id: Icb16b1be23a5dcce7303d7d132db5fd31b3e41f2
Closes-bug: 1742100

commit_message:
Remove trove experimental jobs

These jobs are moved in-tree with change
Iee42e3b667aa114f6c9a6ff03b7da6f0c4708812, remove them.

Also, rename legacy-trove-functional-dsvm-mysql in python-troveclient to
the new in-tree name since python-troveclient does not have a in-tree
zuul.yaml file yet.

Change-Id: I23482a1934c1a63aa951b30d788c436f5e47a7bc
Needed-By: I1f90f21ae482b1097907db472f7f27111e9a87e8

commit_message:
Fix docs for Sphinx 1.6.6

rename included files to not have ".rst" extension,
otherwise they are being scanned for ref targets and found targets are
effectively counted twice (both in file that includes,
and in the file being included), producing a warning/error.

Change-Id: I2eec5b1b16d253998f45e6f0551a92c2ab6f5609
Closes-Bug: #1743780

order to ensure that all subprocesses are killed when the parent dies
unexpectedly, we're associating Win32 job objects to the child processes,
requesting them to be killed when all the job handles are closed. Those
handles are kept by the parent process, being closed when the process
dies.

commit_message:
Windows: allow multiple c-vol backends per service

This change will allow enabling multiple backends within a single
Cinder Volume service on Windows.

We cannot leverage the oslo_service process launcher as it has some
Windows compatibility issues:
- it forks
- it uses eventlet GreenPipe (not available on Windows)
- child processes receive the service objects that should be
launched. Those are not serializable, for which reason we're not
able to pass them without fork support.

For this reason, we'll use the following alternate approach on Windows:
- we're adding another cli argument called 'backend_name', which allows
requesting a certain backend.
- we're adding a Windows process launcher that will just use
subprocess.Popen for each backend, using the above mentioned argument
to request a specific backend. Thus, for each backend, we'll invoke a
command such as the following:
    cinder-volume.exe --backend_name=<backend_name> --config-file=<conf>
- the process launcher will wait for all the subprocesses to exit. In
order to ensure that all subprocesses are killed when the parent dies
unexpectedly, we're associating Win32 job objects to the child processes,
requesting them to be killed when all the job handles are closed. Those
handles are kept by the parent process, being closed when the process
dies.

Depends-On: #Icc2bbe9191e6db685c0fd294abc1d0eb24bc420c

Closes-Bug: #1734334
Change-Id: I80fa111fabd46c7802b89fd6136edd8fa8652d47

Add timeout value into TimeoutException message

I know this is not a necessary patch, however, since it occurs
timout exception, we could easily find the timeout value.

revisions:
[{'created': '2017-08-04 09:42:17.000000000', 'message': 'Bump etcd version to v3.2.4 to enable support for arm64/ppc64le archs

In order to enable devstack on arm64/ppc64le, we need to use etcd >=
v3.2.0 where these architectures have been introduced.

Close-bugs: #1708631

commit_message:
Bump etcd version to v3.2.4 to enable support for arm64/ppc64le archs

In order to enable devstack on arm64/ppc64le, we need to use etcd >=
v3.2.0 where these architectures have been introduced.

Closes-bug: #1708631

Change-Id: I5d017d480b9b5a88eaa3d10de71a4e9dfc2f59fb
Signed-off-by: Kevin Zhao <kevin.zhao@arm.com>

commit_message:
Use keystone session for single tenant remote clients

This class required refactoring to be compatible with newer client
versions, like Nova. We now remove references to novaclient 1.1
and reference the nova version through the existing config var.

We now build a keystone session object which is used to create
the remote clients, as this method is much easier and appears to
be the recommended way.

Closes-Bug: #1662300

Change-Id: I1fec3b1a4c04332d6a14c89c48463ea390c61d74

commit_message:
Fix Metric Statistics period call

Default InfluxDB behaviour is to return a timestamp with no value for
each time period requested. Since we remove those from the return value,
this behaviour breaks pagination because it thinks we hit the limit
but we returned nothing. With fill(none), Influx will not return a
timestamp for a period with no value, which fixes limit and pagination.

Change-Id: I81a7d3610541ef4b333b11e54136ad1cc516687a
Story: 2001457
Task: 6169

commit_message:
[Doc][L3][QoS] Enable floating IP qos

This patch adds documents for floating IP qos feature.
Both neutron server side and L3 agent side settings
will be introduced in this patch.

Partially-Implements blueprint: floating-ip-rate-limit

Change-Id: Ia1f84a5d436220fd22ee1e739242db707d75cf85

commit_message:
Modified the subnet-range parameter to be optional

The subnet-range parameter is only sent now if a valid value exists so
the command will not fail

Change-Id: I5296f5b59bc6d3d3db90a685a8678db9a156eece

commit_message:
Initialize osprofiler in WSGI application

This patch adds missing initialization of OSProfiler
when Cinder API is running as WSGI application.

Change-Id: Ifaffa2d58eeadf5d47fafbdde5538d26bcd346a6

'}, {'created': '2017-10-27 09:00:24.000000000', 'message': 'Update supported transports for iscsi connector

In the case that a compute host with multiple NICs can be connectted to
iscsi storage network, we expect the storage traffic only be
transimitted via storage NIC. This need to define an custom iface and set the
iface.net_ifacename value to the storage interface name.

Unfortunately, the current iscsi connector does not support to use a
custom iface. The _validate_iface_transport will change it to default.
After add tcp to the supported_transports, it is possible to use a
custom iface.

Please get the details as below:
1. CMP001 has three NICs: NIC1 is for management network, NIC2 is
for tenant network, and NIC3 is for storage network. NIC3 can access
storage device via layer 2 network. And NIC1 can access storage device
too, but it can only access via layer 3 network. We hope all the storage
traffic only be transimitted via NIC3, because they are in the same
layer 2 network.
2. Get the NIC3 MAC:
   fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
3. Add new iscsi iface:
   # iscsiadm -m iface --op=new -I tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
   # iscsiadm -m iface -I tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63 --op=update
              -n iface.hwaddress -v fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
4. Edit nova.conf, and change iscsi_iface value:
   iscsi_iface = tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
5. Restart nova compute service:
   # systemctl restart openstack-nova-compute

Without this change, _validate_iface_transport will change the
custom iface tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63 to default due to it cannot find tcp
transport.

Change-Id: I85a62cb6e7f8d8982e97e792d647d38ce5641060
Closes-Bug:#1722432

commit_message:
Update supported transports for iscsi connector

In the case that a compute host with multiple NICs can be connectted to
iscsi storage network, we expect the storage traffic only be
transimitted via storage NIC. This need to define an custom iface and set the
iface.net_ifacename value to the storage interface name.

Unfortunately, the current iscsi connector does not support to use a
custom iface. The _validate_iface_transport will change it to default.
After add tcp to the supported_transports, it is possible to use a
custom iface.

Please get the details as below:
1. CMP001 has three NICs: NIC1 is for management network, NIC2 is
for tenant network, and NIC3 is for storage network. NIC3 can access
storage device via layer 2 network. And NIC1 can access storage device
too, but it can only access via layer 3 network. We hope all the storage
traffic only be transimitted via NIC3, because they are in the same
layer 2 network.
2. Get the NIC3 MAC:
   fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
3. Add new iscsi iface:
   # iscsiadm -m iface --op=new -I tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
   # iscsiadm -m iface -I tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63 --op=update
              -n iface.hwaddress -v fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
4. Edit nova.conf, and change iscsi_iface value:
   iscsi_iface = tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63
5. Restart nova compute service:
   # systemctl restart openstack-nova-compute

Without this change, _validate_iface_transport will change the
custom iface tcp.fa:16:3e:79:fd:63 to default due to it cannot find tcp
transport.

According to this change, we should have a corresponding change to the
nova docs, here is change to nova
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/524443/

Change-Id: I85a62cb6e7f8d8982e97e792d647d38ce5641060
Closes-Bug:#1722432

commit_message:
block sphinx 1.6.6

A behavior change in Sphinx 1.6.6 breaks the documentation build for
several projects that are automatically generating
documentation. Drop the constraint to the previous version and block
1.6.6 until we can sort out how to deal with the change.

https://github.com/sphinx-doc/sphinx/commit/2d99648e9982325bbd670da11df5f809e3134284

Change-Id: Idcacb3c22135acfe5e05eccd607fc0e7e769afb2
Signed-off-by: Doug Hellmann <doug@doughellmann.com>

[{'account_id': 26504, 'date': '2017-09-06 13:51:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2017-09-06 13:51:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Adding DSCP mark and inheritance in OVS and LB tunnels outer header

Adding ability to set DSCP field in OVS tunnels outer header, or
inherit it from the inner header's DSCP value for OVS and linuxbridge.

Change-Id: Ia59753ded73cd23019605668e60cfbc8841e803d
Closes-Bug: #1692951

commit_message:
Add missing iptable rule in snat ns for centralized fips.

The following iptable rule should be added to snat ns:
"-A neutron-l3-agent-snat -j neutron-l3-agent-float-snat",
or the snat rule will take effect instead of centralized fips
when accessing to the outside for vms.
Closes-Bug: #1735866

Change-Id: I286283bfb4dbf935a34c5919ee0af5225e75fac9
(cherry picked from commit 0f08b2c625d9158e7dce80ff2d01ffd273e0d9c3)

commit_message:
Remove the check about related_to

What we want is that when mongodb is do cluster-grow, by
_group_shard_instances[1] to determine which instance is a
replica set, this function in a replica sets can allow
an instance without related_to opintion, which same as our
originally planned is the same[2].
But now because of this check, result if have any instance
without related_to will be error, this check was placed in
the front of _group_shard_instances, resulting in we can
not achieve the originally planned. My idea is to
get rid of this check,with use _group_shard_instances to
see whether related_to meet the requirements for grow.

[1]:https://github.com/openstack/trove/blob/master/trove/common/strategies/cluster/experimental/mongodb/api.py#L496
[2]:https://specs.openstack.org/openstack/trove-specs/specs/liberty/cluster-scaling.html#add-replica-set

Change-Id: I9e2f441d1434617077368e05efe95032fab01d4f

Rename tox_venvlist (2/2)

For consistency with the tox jobs, use tox_envlist instead of
tox_venvlist.

We need first to add a new parameter, then change the job, then
remove the old parameter.

commit_message:
Add administrative operations for some resources

Now, admin user could list/show/delete/update most of qinling
resources, except function deletion. Because function deletion
needs to delete the trust created for qinling service by its
owner, only end user has the authority to delete their trust.

Implements: blueprint qinling-admin-operations
Change-Id: I9ec4df59fbf8ac50c96d9677dd74c54677b307a5

The fake libvirt driver generates disk xml for disks of various types,
but assumes file type for the source attribute. This causes a parse
failure for block devices.

No tests currently rely on this. I encountered it whilst writing a test
which did use a fake block volume, and it was a severe headscratcher
when the resulting parsed configuration had an empty source_path: being
a block device it was looking for source/dev, not source/file. I
ultimately didn't use that test, but would like to save somebody the
hairloss in the future.

Change-Id: I5cf594cb0cc8310ccfa4f31d981803ce152a69d5
"}]
commit_message:
Fix fake libvirt XML generation for disks

The fake libvirt driver generates disk xml for disks of various types,
but assumes file type for the source attribute. This causes a parse
failure for block devices.

No tests currently rely on this. I encountered it whilst writing a test
which did use a fake block volume, and it was a severe headscratcher
when the resulting parsed configuration had an empty source_path: being
a block device it was looking for source/dev, not source/file. I
ultimately didn't use that test, but would like to save somebody the
hairloss in the future.

Change-Id: I5cf594cb0cc8310ccfa4f31d981803ce152a69d5

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Add condition to create container images download script.

It is also interesting for the role to support
the option of passing by an already existing
script that handles the container images downloading.

By adding this conditional we avoid rewritting the
content of the passed script when setting the var
to false.

Change-Id: I8b82071dfa7d440c7c840ffb9bcdf006843b6d97
(cherry picked from commit 6377a43a1721404ba32cf558e3493d3018c97ab3)

commit_message:
Reduce race condition with timeout for ansible run

When we run command with "timeout" we need to have spare minutes
to prevent race condition when zuul stops the job before we do it.

Change-Id: I9f5eb7133e205e4f667c7b56f20def4f44d89ced

commit_message:
WIP rbd: Allow encrypted volumes

This enables the creation and potential seeding of LUKS encrypted rbd
volumes using the qemu-img utility provided by QEMU 2.10.

Depends-On: Ibfa64f18bbd2fb70db7791330ed1a64fe61c1355
Change-Id: I404070e2428cdf404b576d1d9da5b917f9be11d1
Implements: blueprint libvirt-qemu-native-luks

object passed in, but create_volume doesn't.

This is needed for drivers to interact with
Barbican for encryption key management.

Change-Id: I10cc57aaa9c49e75f54508f2c08061e17fa52146
"}]
commit_message:
Add context to driver.create_volume()

Many of our driver calls already have a context
object passed in, but create_volume doesn't.

This is needed for drivers to interact with
Barbican for encryption key management.

Change-Id: I10cc57aaa9c49e75f54508f2c08061e17fa52146

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-01-16 10:22:52.000000000', 'message': "Drop the container_actions table foreign key

container_actions.container_uuid is a foreign key of
container.uuid. When user delete a container, zun will delete the
data of the container from database. With this foreign key contrain,
it will generate error in deleting container data.

This commit remove the container_actions table's foreign key. Using
orm.relationship to join container_actions.container_uuid and
container.uuid.

commit_message:
Drop the container_actions table foreign key

container_actions.container_uuid is a foreign key of
container.uuid. When user delete a container, zun will delete the
data of the container from database. With this foreign key contrain,
it will generate error in deleting container data.

This commit remove the container_actions table's foreign key. Using
orm.relationship to join container_actions.container_uuid and
container.uuid.

Change-Id: Iac25adc69495826e6d5b0109eb729a0387e63c0b
